#' Create a Marriage Network Graph
#' 
#' This function creates an undirected graph from marriage data within a specified time window
#' before a given election year.
#'
#' @param marriage_data A data frame containing marriage records with columns:
#'   - year: The year of the marriage
#'   - husband_familyname_std: Standardized husband's family name
#'   - wife_familyname_std: Standardized wife's family name
#' @param election_year The target election year
#' @param years_before Number of years before the election to include (default: 20)
#' 
#' @return An igraph graph object representing the marriage network
#' @importFrom igraph graph_from_data_frame
#' @importFrom dplyr filter
#' @export
create_marriage_network <- function(marriage_data, election_year, years_before = 20) {
  marriages_window <- marriage_data %>%
    filter(year <= election_year & year >= election_year - years_before)
  
  marriage_network <- graph_from_data_frame(
    marriages_window,
    directed = FALSE,
    vertices = unique(c(marriages_window$husband_familyname_std, 
                       marriages_window$wife_familyname_std))
  )
  
  return(marriage_network)
}
@

According to the traditional myth, the Republic of Venice was ruled by a selfless and harmonious patrician elite committed to the common good.\citep{crouzet2002venice,muir1981civic}%Muir Ch. 1
Central to this narrative was the notion of equality among its  members before the law. Historical reality, however, fell short of this idealised image: political rivalries recurred throughout the Republic's history, and  access to the most prestigious offices was largely concentrated in the hands of a relatively small number of families.\citep{grubb1986myths,cracco1979,queller86}  For the Renaissance, scholars have identified a division within the patriciate between a small group of leading families, which controlled  a disproportionate share of major offices, and a broader body of lesser families; the dominant group comprised around forty \emph{casate}--twenty-four belonging to the  \emph{longhi} or \emph{case vecchie}, that is, families of the most ancient standing, and sixteen to the  \emph {curti} or\emph{case nuove}. Despite their prestige, these forty families represented  only 22 per cent of the 181 noble lineages,\footnote{\ Most of these forty families were large and therefore commanded a  proportionally greater share of votes in the Great Council by virtue of their numerous members, yet they remained a numerical minority. One estimate places the \emph{case vecchie} at roughly one third of the votes in the Great Council at the beginning of the sixteenth century.} %22% da Cojniacki1973, pag. 51, un terzo (35%) da Finlay pag. 93
a fact that raises an important question: how did such a minority--often portrayed as divided along the \emph{longhi}/\emph{curti} line--could come to dominate political office? More broadly,  the role played by the remaining, less prestigious families has yet to be fully clarified.\citep{chojnacki1973search,burke1974}%Chojnacki1973, p. ,burke1974 a pag. 21--22.
 
To address this issue, it is necessary to consider the institutional framework of the Venetian constitution. The Republic comprised over one hundred major magistracies, including the dogeship, most of which were filled by the Great Council through electoral procedures combining sortition and successive rounds of voting, often requiring qualified majorities exceeding sixty percent. The frequency of elections and the high thresholds required fostered alliances among noble families. %Finlay p. 3
Marriage was central to this process. Far from being merely a private arrangement, it functioned as a political instrument through which patrician houses strategically structured  alliances,  consolidated electoral support, and secured access to office. 

 Because the Venetian Republic regarded factional division as a threat to its stability and systematically discouraged open expressions of conflict, explicit evidence of political alignments is scarce. For this reason, this paper analyses a  network of marriages linking noble families, formerly assembled by\citep{PugaTrefler}, in order to identify patterns of cohesion and division within the patriciate. In  particular, it seeks to determine whether these divisions followed lines of ancestry (i.e. \emph{longhi} versus \emph{curti}), wealth (rich versus poor), or other as yet unidentified forms of political alignment, and how such patterns evolved over time \dots CONTINUARE QUANDO SARANNO PIU' CHIARE LE RESEARCH QUESTION
 
 %Da qui in giù ancora da rivedere fino a methodology


We can formulate the following research questions:\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Research Question 1} Is there evidence of factions in the social network during the {\em ducale} era? If there is, are {\em lunghi} and {\em curti} {\em case} in different communities or clearly separated?
\item {\bf Research Question 2} Whatever the division in factions, what is the position of the elected doge's family in the social network at the moment of election? Is there some claim that can be made on social status or position for every family one of whose members was elected as doge?
\item {\bf Research Question 3} Is there any way to characterize the {\em ducali} families other than "case {\em nuove} one of whose member became a doge"? Is there any specific social status associated to these families?
\end{itemize}

That might help us understand, or at least discard possibilities, why a group of up and coming families, the {\em curti} families, managed to overcome the {\em lunghi} families for several centuries, putting the member of one of their families as doge, something that a priori implies some strategic planning, as well as tactical maneuvering at the point of election.

We will try to draw the implications on the results above on our current understanding of the historic dynamics behind the Republica Serenissima in its heyday.

\section{Venetian patriciate in the Renaissance}

The Venetian nobility was formally established with the Serrata (closure) of 1297, a measure that restricted access to the Great Council \cite{serrata}. This law granted membership to all individuals who had served on the Great Council during the previous four years, as well as--subject to the approval of the Council--to others who had taken part in government over the preceding thirty years. In 1323, a subsequent law made this status hereditary: all male sons of members of the Great Council were automatically admitted upon reaching the age of twenty-five. At first, the legislation did not require the formal registration of those admitted to the Great Council. As a result, new admissions to the noble body continued, to a certain extent, for approximately three decades \citep{chojnacki1973search}. 

Despite its name, the Serrata did not lead to a reduction in the size of the Great Council. On the contrary, the reform resulted in a marked expansion of its membership: the number of councillors increased from an average of less than three hundred to more than one thousand.\citep{chojnacki97, raines2003cooptazione} Yet, beyond its numerical expansion, the Serrata fundamentally transformed the nature of the institution: What had previously been a relatively small body of members elected for limited terms became a larger hereditary assembly. In this way, access to political power was restricted to a clearly defined group of families, turning the Venetian patriciate into a closed and hereditary caste.

In this early period, additions to the ranks of the nobility continued, to some extent, for roughly three decades. By the mid-fourteenth century, however, access to noble status had become significantly more restricted. Thereafter, and until the mid-seventeenth century,  new admissions were rare. The only major  wave of aggregations occurred in 1381, when approximately thirty families were admitted to the patriciate in recognition of their financial and military support during the War of Chioggia.\footnote{\ A new and more substantial wave of admissions occurred in the seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, when the Republic--faced with the fiscal pressures of prolonged warfare, particularly during the War of Candia and the Morean War--opened access to the patriciate in exchange for considerable financial contributions.} 

This closure did not give rise to major episodes of social unrest or sustained protest among those excluded. Social conflict in Venice generally remained limited, in part because the patriciate was able to preserve stability by ensuring justice and an adequate food supply for the lower classes.\citep{pullan1971rich}  By contrast, tensions were more evident within the patriciate itself. Although the principle of one man, one vote formally applied, the Great Council was marked by multiple internal divisions, shaped by differences in wealth, lineage, family size, and social standing. Precisely because all members were formally equal within the Council, leading lineages sought alternative means of distinction. The closure of the Great Council thus encouraged the drafting of lists identifying some of the founding families of Venice as the most prestigious, families whose origins were traditionally traced back to the ninth century.  As discussed by Raines \citep[p. 434]{raines2006invention1}, these lists were revised over time, and the composition of the group was not entirely fixed: although some names varied across early versions,  the composition of the group appears to have stabilised from the fifteenth century onward. It included twenty-four families, commonly referred to as the \emph{case vecchie}  (old houses) or \emph{longhi} (long): Badoer, Barozzi, Baseggio, Bembo, Bragadin, Contarini, Corner, Dandolo, Dolfin, Falier, Giustiniani, Gradenigo, Memmo, Michiel, Morosini, Polani, Querini, Salamon, Sanuto, Soranzo, Tiepolo, Zane, Zeno, Zorzi.   The remaining families were identified as \emph{case nuove} (new houses) or \emph{curti} (short). Those admitted after the War of Chioggia, in particular, came to be known as the \emph{case nuovissime} (newest houses). \citep{chojnacki1973search}, \citep[p. 92-96]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}  and \citep[p. 780]{raines2006invention2}.%(Chojnacki Search, pp. 49-50)  

The antiquity of lineage was not the only factor that distinguished families within the Great Council. There were also significant differences in wealth as well as in the number of male members each family could send to the Council. These distinctions often overlapped. Within the patriciate, prestige and wealth did not necessarily coincide: some recently ennobled families accumulated great fortunes through trade, while certain older and more prestigious lineages--or branches within them--experienced significant economic decline.\footnote{\ For instance, at the end of the fifteenth century, Priuli recorded in his diaries that about three quarters of the patriciate were ``poor,'' that is, dependent on paid public office for their subsistence.\citep[p. 73]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}.}

This diverse body of patricians sitting in the Great Council was responsible for selecting, from among its own members, those who would govern the Republic, including the Doge. The Council's principal function was in fact electoral: it appointed the magistracies and the main colleges of the Republic. The offices to be filled numbered in the hundreds, not including minor posts, and most were of short duration. As a result, the Great Council met regularly to carry out elections. These procedures were generally based on a combination of sortition and voting and required extremely high quorum thresholds.  For the most important offices, the electoral process could be extremely elaborate, involving multiple rounds of sortition and voting. The election of the Doge, for example, consisted of ten rounds and the formation of five different electoral committees. In the final ballot, twenty-five out of forty-one votes were required, a quorum just over 60 percent, but larger majorities were necessary in earlier rounds of the procedure.\citep{molinari2020republic} Another common feature was the indirect nature of many elections: the Council would often vote to select individuals who would in turn choose the officeholder. The concentration of the final decision in the hands of a small group made it easier to reach compromises.

In this context, success in elections depended on securing dependable alliances and supporters, frequently consolidated through marriage.\footnote{\emph{Broglio} likewise helped  to build clienteles, especially in the later period  of the Republic, when impoverished nobles--known as \emph{Sguizeri} (Swiss), in reference  to the mercenary soldiers--were effectively paid  in return for their  votes,
%anche a pagina 20dice dopo Agnadello, 
a practice that the Republic consistently sought to curb. In Venice even \emph{broglio onesto}, i.e. the open solicitation of electoral support, was officially forbidden. \citep[p. 204-218]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} and \citep[ch. 3]{queller86}} For patrician families, marriage was therefore a central element in the political and social management of the family since in-laws could become both business partners and political allies.\citep{raines2013rameau}, \citep[p.81-82]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} %Raines a pag. 130]
These alliances could benefit all parties involved: families of lower standing improved their status through advantageous matches, whereas more prestigious lineages gained substantial dowries and expanded their political backing.\citep{chojnacki1975dowries}. For this reason, given the lack of systematic evidence on the political alignments, the study of marriage ties can offer valuable insight into patterns of cohesion and division within the patriciate.

The present analysis applies this approach to the election of the Doge. As the Republic’s highest office, the dogeship provides a suitable case for examining political alliances. It is therefore useful to begin by outlining the qualifications typically expected of candidates.

Numerous qualities were expected of a nobleman aspiring to this office.\citep[p.141--]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}. The position was typically reserved for men of advanced age,\footnote{\ Given that the office was held for life, candidates considered too young were generally excluded \citep{smith2021long}. Having too many sons could also be a disadvantage for fear of nepotism.\citep[p. 134]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance}} who had previously held multiple offices with distinction. Service in high-ranking posts--such as ambassadorships--and a university education were regarded as important qualifications. Since both required substantial financial resources, wealth effectively became a necessary attribute for aspiring candidates.\citep[p. 18--26]{burke1974}, \citep[p. 28--29]{davis1962}, % per eccezioni Raines invenzioni  p.287-288 Alcune eccezioni di doge che non venivano da famiglie grandi, ricche o prestigiose: Nicolò da Ponte (1578) e Francesco Erizzo (1631). Da ponte: il suo arrivo al dogato frutto di circostanze uniche create dalla lotta per il potere fra famiglie ducai e famiglie del patriziato anziano.  
Since these qualifications were often shared by several eligible nobles, competition rarely turned on credentials alone; what ultimately distinguished candidates was the breadth of the support they could mobilise. 

In Renaissance chronicles, ducal elections appear structured around a division between the \emph{longhi} and the \emph{curti}. Following a prolonged phase in which the doges were largely drawn from the {\em case vecchie}, the \emph{case nuove} are said to have excluded them from the dogeship between 1382 and 1612; the nineteen doges elected during this interval were later described as the \emph{ducali}.\citep[780-792]{raines2006invention2}

The extent to which this opposition represented a genuine and sustained political conflict, however, remains uncertain. As \citep{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} has observed,  %pagina 92-93 anche rainesinventiona pag 443 la mette in dubbio
although the \emph{longhi} were excluded from the dogeship during this period, their representation in other major offices appears to have remained broadly proportional to their numerical strength in the Great Council. This suggests that their political marginalisation may have been more limited than the traditional narrative implies.
The chronology of the rivalry is equally problematic. A seventeenth-century account dates the alleged pact among the \emph{curti} families to 1450, even if the actual exclusion can be dated far back, while episodes of particularly intense competition seem concentrated in specific elections—most notably those of 1486 and 1512.\citep[145--154]{finlay1980politicsrenaissance} \citep[p. 439--440]{raines2006invention1}.%Alvise da Mosto dice dal 1414 pag. XLII
 
One possible interpretation, which has not yet been systematically explored, is that the so-called conspiracy reflected not a rigid division between \emph{longhi} and \emph{curti}, but rather a struggle for dominance among the largest and most powerful clans of the city, with many of the smaller \emph{curti} families at least tacitly aligned with the ducali.


